close_symbols: enum MHD_Result and constants (MHD_NO, MHD_HTTP_SERVICE_UNAVAILABLE, MHD_HTTP_OK)
libmicrohttpd request-handler contract: con_cls/req_cls lifecycle (how *req_cls is initialized, preserved and when reset) — e.g. MHD_start_daemon / callback documentation
semantics of upload_data and upload_data_size in libmicrohttpd callbacks (how/when handler is called for POST and when upload_data_size is non-zero)
explanation:
For deciding whether any statements in ahc_echo are dead (i.e. their removal would not change program behaviour) you must know not only the local code but the external data and library invocation semantics that determine which branches execute and what side effects matter. Each listed symbol is needed for the reasons below:

- struct handler_param (definition)
  - The code reads param->response_page and calls strlen on it. To determine whether the final response branch (creating/queuing the OK response) has any observable effect, you must know how handler_param is defined and initialized (is response_page non-empty, constant, or never set?). If response_page is always empty or identical to BUSYPAGE, behaviour may differ and code might be redundant.

- BUSYPAGE (string/macro definition)
  - The POST "busy" branch builds a response from BUSYPAGE. To know whether that branch produces an observable effect (and thus is not dead) you must know the BUSYPAGE contents and whether it differs from other responses.

- enum MHD_Result and constants (MHD_NO, MHD_HTTP_SERVICE_UNAVAILABLE, MHD_HTTP_OK)
  - The function returns these values and passes status codes to MHD_queue_response. Understanding their semantic meaning in the wider program is necessary to judge whether removing code that returns/queues those results would change behaviour.

- MHD_queue_response
  - This call performs the observable side effect of queuing/sending an HTTP response. Whether the call is removable (i.e. dead) depends on its semantics and side effects. You must inspect this symbol to know if calling it is required for correct behaviour.

- MHD_create_response_from_buffer_static
  - Creates the response object passed to MHD_queue_response. If this function is a no-op or returns a shared static object, that affects whether the surrounding code is redundant. Its behaviour impacts whether code that builds responses is necessary.

- MHD_destroy_response
  - Called after queueing. If destroying responses has required side effects (resource management, reference counting), removing those calls could change behaviour. You must know its semantics.

- libmicrohttpd request-handler contract: con_cls/req_cls lifecycle (how *req_cls is initialized, preserved and when reset) — e.g. MHD_start_daemon / callback documentation
  - The branch and the POST-handling logic hinge on the value and lifetime of *req_cls (the code compares &aptr with *req_cls, stores &aptr, later sets *req_cls = NULL). Whether the &aptr branch ever executes (or is redundant) depends entirely on how the library initializes and preserves req_cls across invocations for the same request. You must inspect the daemon/callback registration and the documented semantics (often referred to as con_cls/req_cls contract) to determine if that branch is ever taken or required.

- semantics of upload_data and upload_data_size in libmicrohttpd callbacks (how/when handler is called for POST and when upload_data_size is non-zero)
  - The code contains special logic for POST requests (always respond busy on the first invocation). Whether that POST-specific branch is ever reached (and whether upload handling causes multiple invocations) depends on how the library invokes the handler for POST requests and how upload_data/upload_data_size are used. Understanding that calling pattern is necessary to decide if the POST branch (and its response creation) is live code.

Together these symbols and semantics let an analyzer determine: (a) whether the conditional branches in ahc_echo can execute at all in normal operation, and (b) whether the calls within those branches produce observable effects (network responses, resource changes) such that removing them would alter program behaviour. Without these symbols you cannot conclude whether parts of ahc_echo are dead code under the MISRA rule.
